  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Vocative (النداء)",
      "titleArabic": "النداء",
      "content": [
        "The vocative (النداء) is used to call or address someone. The most common vocative particle is يَا (yā), which is equivalent to 'O' or 'Hey' in English.",
        "The noun after يَا is called المنادى (the one being called). Its case depends on its structure - it can be nominative (مرفوع) or accusative (منصوب)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "يَا is the most common vocative particle",
        "Other particles include أَيَا، هَيَا، أَيْ، أَ (rare)",
        "يَا can call both near and far, while أَيَا and هَيَا are for distant",
        "أَيْ and أَ are for calling someone close"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "يَا مُحَمَّدُ", "english": "O Muhammad!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا طَالِبُ", "english": "O student!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا أُسْتَاذُ", "english": "O teacher!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا رَبِّ", "english": "O Lord!" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Types of Vocative",
      "titleArabic": "أنواع المنادى",
      "content": [
        "The vocative noun can be definite (معرفة) or indefinite (نكرة), and this affects its grammatical case.",
        "A single definite noun (المنادى المفرد المعرفة) takes a ḍamma (nominative form), but it is considered منصوب محلاً (accusative in place)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Single proper noun: يَا مُحَمَّدُ (nominative ending, accusative in meaning)",
        "Indefinite intended: يَا رَجُلًا (accusative ending)",
        "Idafa construction: يَا عَبْدَ اللهِ (accusative)",
        "With adjective: يَا أَيُّهَا الطَّالِبُ (O student!)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "يَا عَبْدَ اللهِ", "english": "O Abdullah (servant of God)!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا أَيُّهَا النَّاسُ", "english": "O people!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا أَيَّتُهَا النَّفْسُ", "english": "O soul!" },
        { "arabic": "يَا طَالِبًا لِلْعِلْمِ", "english": "O seeker of knowledge!" }
      ]
    }
  ],
